Russia and Turkey: an alliance of outsiders?
A gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and officially declare the eight-month battle over words and economic sanctions over.
But when Vladimir Putin greeted his Turkish counterpart in the gilded hall of St. Petersburg's palace, I got the clear impression that Ankara wants more of this reconciliation.
Yes, there was a shake of hands.
But Putin's smile seemed forced, and he didn't exude much warmth, even by his own restrained standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, constantly spoke about his "dear friend" Putin - five times, according to one report.
I messed up the bills.
He also vowed that relations with Russia would return not only to pre-crisis levels, but even better.
The next day, newspapers here described Erdogan as if nothing bad had ever happened.
In my opinion, his enthusiasm reflected the opposite.
But the coolness radiating from Putin showed that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
In fact, the cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening remarks: when Turkey shot down a Russian warplane on the Syrian border.
Moscow's reaction at that time was furious.
Putin attacked, accusing Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The insult was even worse when it came from a supposed friend.
Rebuilding true trust will be difficult, perhaps impossible.
The opinion of the Russian public has also changed since November.
For months, the state-controlled media led an astonishing, profound attack on Ankara.
Suddenly, it seemed that the Turks were to blame for everything.
Most serious were the accusations by senior officials that Erdogan's own family has profited from illegal oil trade from ISIS-controlled areas of Syria.
He has emphatically denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message was that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin received the apology he demanded from President Erdogan.
Russia achieved some kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of agreeing a truce are clear.
First, Erdogan needs all possible friends after he was nearly ousted from power in last month's failed coup.
The constant terrorist attacks in Turkey have also clearly shaken him.
In addition, there is an economic motive.
Russia's economic sanctions have been heavy, especially the ban on charter flights, which usually carry several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast each year.
The number has fallen by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, local tour operators and charter airlines will certainly be relieved when flights finally resume.
They are hoping for a late-season rush to the Mediterranean.
And already this week, state TV has predicted cheaper fruits and vegetables after agricultural imports from Turkey are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as the report of the Vedemosti newspaper put it.
But the visit also had political added value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what is seen as a weak response to an attempted coup.
Add to that the long-standing resentment over the snail's fast-paced EU accession negotiations, and Putin emerges, eager to exploit the coolness and erode Turkey's ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly scored points in Ankara, where he called after the attempted revolution to support the designated authorities.
Of course, this is a given for Moscow, which has its own deep-seated fear of regime change.
So this meeting in a grand seaside palace made it possible for Russia and Turkey to introduce an "alliance of outsiders," as one analyst described the situation to me: two countries that feel abandoned and mistreated by the West, joining forces.
However, the two have major differences despite public reconciliation.
The key problem is Syria, where Moscow has recently adapted itself to the role of peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey support opposing sides.
It may be telling that after nearly three hours of preliminary discussions, the presidents told the press that they hadn't even addressed the issue.
The Turkish president deliberately avoided answering a question about their differences, while Putin chose to highlight them.
There is no clear consensus on where they can look for common ground on Syria.
After months of open hostility, and given the possibility of total disaster when NATO member Turkey shoots down a Russian warplane, it is certainly better for the two leaders to be on speaking terms again.
