Pokémon Go is a respectable hunt for health and happiness
It's fascinating to see how the world is changing.
Over the past decade, many have worried that teenagers and children no longer go out to play, preferring to spend their free time looking at screens.
Pokémon Go makes people get up from the couch and participate in some activity.
Screen time was originally limited to television, then video games, and now, more recently, smartphones.
So it's great to see that technology and outdoor activity aren't mutually exclusive.
I'm referring, of course, to a craze called Pokémon Go. An app based on characters originally developed in the 1990s for video games (later they spawned cartoons, playing cards, and other sequels).
Like many pop culture phenomena, its popularity had been somewhat diluted before the release of this new game in the United States, Australia, and New Zealand in early July.
After that, the release of the game in other countries was postponed, as the huge popularity overloaded the servers.
In just days, Pokémon Go had more users than Tinder and almost as many as Twitter.
So how does it work?
In a nutshell, players use their smartphones to search for Pokémon that are tracked using GPS and can be "photographed" (using a screenshot of their phone) or "caught" once found.
The generation that played the game when they were younger has joined the craze and jumped up from the couch to join the search.
In the United States, the game has led to a significant increase in the daily steps of the "average person".
Apple Watch app Cardiogram, which tracks 35,000 users, recently told The Washington Post that within two days of the game's release, the number of people exercising 30 minutes a day jumped from 45 percent to 53 percent among users tracked by Cardiogram.
The company does not know who is playing Pokémon Go, it only sees training level information.
Many public health campaigns' calls to "find 30," "get up from the couch," and "be active every day" have yielded no results because most public health warnings are boring and passed on by people who look unhappy.
However, the importance of exercise cannot be underestimated.
People who exercise regularly have a lower risk of developing cancer or depression.
Being active helps with weight management, high blood pressure and diabetes. Its benefits are too diverse to list here.
The beauty of Pokémon Go is that it makes people go out and do something they enjoy.
This covers the three pillars of health: exercise, fresh air and sunshine, and fun.
Some people even make new friends while hunting.
As usual, disapproving spoilers of joy look for things to complain about.
Yes, someone can walk towards the door.
So what?
There has been a breakthrough.
Although there used to be apps like Fitbit that could track activity, they didn't give a reason to move in the same way as this game.
The novelty charm disappears and the use fades in time.
However, due to the success of Pokémon, there will be other games that combine apps and virtual reality with real-world activity, helping many people who hunt to be more active, fit, and healthier.
