A little bit ahead of the crook - criminal intelligence helps solve crimes and reveals serious crime - ESS.fi
Since the beginning of 2014, each of Finland's 11 police departments has had an RTA (Criminal Intelligence and Analysis Unit).
The operation of the unit is outwardly invisible.
In the Häme Police Department, the unit consists of a total of four police officers in Lahti and Hämeenlinna.
It is led by a sergeant stationed in Lahti.
The officer's supervisor is the Chief Inspector in Lahti.
In addition, the unit's strength includes a civilian dedicated to information technology in Hämeenlinna.
Everyone works in civilian clothes.
The unit has proven its usefulness and necessity, says Deputy Police Chief Tero Seppänen.
The RTA unit produces various reports for the rest of the police.
In Häme, it has, among other things, collected information on asylum seekers.
The latest reform of working methods
The establishment of analysis units is the latest reform of police working methods.
The aim has been to prevent crime, i.e. to make it less and less common for the police to go to the scene with whistles only when they receive an alarm.
With the help of the data collected and analysed by the unit, daily police activities are targeted where they are most needed.
As part of the reform of police administration, one criminal intelligence centre was established in the country, three national units under it and a separate criminal intelligence unit for each police department.
The PTR Centre, which operates in Vantaa in connection with the National Bureau of Investigation, manages operations nationwide.
As the name implies, the PTR units employ people from the Police, Customs and the Border Guard.
RTA units, on the other hand, work in areas divided according to police departments and are tasked with providing information to both local police forces and national units.
Reconnaissance extends beyond one's own area
While an individual police officer is aware of what has happened during his or her 12-hour shift, the task of the RTA unit is to know what is happening throughout the police department.
Intelligence also extends beyond the boundaries of one's own institution, because so does crime.
Those working in the RTA unit have better computer skills than the basic police.
The unit uses registers, an emergency task database and observations to draw the attention of the police to new phenomena, prolific criminals or similar crimes.
This is called serialization and is one of the most important tools for criminal intelligence.
All people have their own way of acting.
The handprint can also be seen in the work, whether it is honest or criminal.
Based on the method of making, a certain image of the perpetrator is formed.
Serialisation can be carried out either on the basis of the method of the act or on the basis of the person, depending on which one the police have more information about.
Criminals learn from their mistakes
RTA employees do not walk around town with collars up, but their work is not fully public.
Both their own methods and those used by criminals are not disclosed, as this could lead to professional criminals developing their activities in order to prevent police attempts to prevent crime.
The police will publicly disclose the methods if they anticipate that they pose a threat.
Such a case was, for example, reported in the news at the beginning of the summer, a method of marking empty dwellings used in burglaries.
In it, the perpetrators put a stick, pin or piece of tape on the front door of the apartment to test whether the residents were really traveling.
The pre-trial investigation material is public at least to the parties involved.
The analysis unit has found that the most professional criminals learn from the mistakes they make.
The smartest ones order the minutes of the district court, which may, for example, show that fingerprints have been found at the scene.
Next time, the thieves will go out with gloves on.
Deputy Police Chief Tero Seppänen from the Häme Police, Chief Inspector Tuomo Lepola from the Eastern Finland Police, Detective Chief Inspector Sami Joutjärvi from Joensuu Police Station and Detective Inspector Arto Tuomela from the National Bureau of Investigation were interviewed for the article.
The police collect and analyse information that is used to plan practical activities.
This is due to a decrease in the amount of manpower and funding.
The first steps towards the new way of working were taken already 30 years ago.
The latest change was the three-phase Pora reform, which ended at the end of 2013.
National cooperation collects information from outside the department and Finland.
