The destination of vinyl: who actually buys records?
Lonely, middle-aged men love vinyls.
Before rushing to fill the comment section with irritated insults written by the pseudonym Not AllLoneMiddle-AgedMen, note that this argument is based on real data.
According to YouGov, the much-talked about revival of records is not because more and more people born in this millennium are getting excited about the novelty of physical objects, but because of the longing for middle age.
Apparently, those who have recently bought a vinyl record are most likely to be between 45 and 54 years old.
In fact, those in the 18-24 age group are least likely to buy records.
It's not just about collecting for amateurs, it's also about emotional significance: older vinyl buyers are slightly more likely to keep their emotions inside (56% vs 53%) and enjoy being alone (69% vs 66%).
But are YouGov's results correct?
If this blog were a television news report, the camera would follow me as I walk through a busy street in Soho, wearing a modest gray suit. I would gesture briskly before stopping, forming a cup from my hands, and saying something authoritative, like, "Let's investigate further."
Let's explore the issue in more detail.
While Soho's charm and dirt are slowly being removed — hotels, chain restaurants and stores, and office supply stores now fill buildings that once housed independent stores — a handful of stunning specialized record stores still remain.
For the next section, I would probably ask the camera to stop shooting for a while as I stand very close to different men in some of these shops trying to judge by observing their age and emotional temperament.
Stuart, 55, from Glasgow, whom I follow from Sister Ray (counter: two young women, three middle-aged men) to Reckless Records (counter: eight middle-aged men, one woman, probably in his twenties), spends his afternoon in London meeting up, and goes around the shops to spend a few hours.
I ask if he is a collector.
"I guess I am," he says.
I have about 3000 or 4000 discs.
These plates, shown in the photo above (he emailed the shot, I didn't follow him home), cover the walls of his living room.
The reason for acquiring such a huge number of records and singles is partly due to his disposable income: now he can buy records that he could not afford when they were originally released, and he can rebuy the ones he sold when he was young and penniless.
"A lot of the material I bought is from the late '60s and early '70s, records that were released when I was 11 or 12, records that I was probably a little too young to get," he says.
He agrees that record buyers are more likely to be introverts who enjoy their own company, adding, "I don't smoke or drink much.
This is my vice."
Wez, 25, who works at Sister Ray, also believes many of the clients she encounters fit YouGov's profile.
However, he has noticed a new wave of people who have been affected by media enthusiasm. People who have heard that records have come back into fashion and have felt the need to buy back their old records.
From the conversations I have had, people have gotten rid of their collections, usually in 1998 or 1999.
Customers who sold their vinyls to buy CDs are now selling their CDs to buy their records back," he says.
This may explain the increase in the number of vinyl awakeners of a certain age.
But what about the alleged emotional significance of the albums?
In a shop like Phonica, it takes a few seconds to realize that record stores offer a comforting community of like-minded guys.
According to Wez, some older customers have been particularly offended by the contactless payment system.
Some vinyl fans may be overwhelmed by the digital world and choose to rely on the permanence of familiar album covers; objects that evoke memories of teenage lucky days.
"I think sometimes it can be about filling a gap or some kind of comfort that owning objects creates," Wez says.
As a collector myself, I admit that this is true, and I believe it to be true for many people.
It's an easy way to fill your thoughts.
"We're like their social workers!" another worker said abruptly from the stack of records.
An April ICM poll revealed that nearly 50% of people who had bought a vinyl record in the previous month had not yet listened to it.
The survey also found that 41% have a turntable they never use, while 7% of vinyl buyers don't have one.
At this point in the news report, I would probably look seriously concerned as I scroll through the stack of bossa nova collections.
This "reward" aspect of revival is something that Jonny, 42, who works at Sounds of the Universe (counter: three middle-aged men), has also noticed.
"Someone recently came in and said, 'I don't have a turntable, but I want to buy a Radiohead record so we can put it on the shelf,'" he says.
It is not a large percentage, but it will definitely happen.
More product, less music.
We have people who say, "I don't have a record player."
Not older people, but younger people, late teenagers who are just getting excited about it.
Foppi, which nowadays has almost an entire floor reserved for vinyls, has a much more diverse audience when I arrive.
Couples in their seventies, tourists taking photos, teenage boys and middle-aged women.
Although the atmosphere is less relaxed than in the previously mentioned shops - the speakers are fresh with Wild Beast's latest synth and sex-filled pop, rather than improvisational jazz - it's great to see different customers.
None of them seem particularly lonely, but it's hard to prove a nagging psychological trauma by standing next to someone for 30 seconds.
Elanora, 27, has been walking around Fop for a few minutes looking at the various records on sale.
He's window shopping, not spending a lot of money.
He says he doesn't make much money, so collecting records isn't really an option.
"It's expensive.
It's easy to listen to music either on your computer or through something else, but the beauty of vinyl is..." He sighs in love.
"I don't know how to explain - it's really unique."
My last stop is said to have awakened a new generation of vinyl lovers: Urban Outfitters.
While trying to look like I'm researching denim shorts, I'm observing a group of teenage girls briefly gathering around Polaroid cameras before father and daughter ponder buying Crosley's turntable.
On the left is a staircase with a wall covered in records by Adele, Jeff Buckley, Amy Winehouse, and Fleetwood Mac: a mix of contemporary music and classics, essential records from any average collection.
No one looks at them - perhaps because they are just decorations, and some are so high that it would be impossible to touch them.
It is purely "art vinyl".
But given that even a little attention these items get can mean more money for the industry and send a few customers to Soho for more, there's not much to complain about.
It comes as no surprise that the segment of the population that is more likely to have more time and money is also the one that spends the most on luxury items such as vinyl.
But while my findings suggest that YouGov's results are accurate, at least for record stores in Soho, they don't rule out the large number of female collectors and vinyl lovers that exist in the real world, record stores, and online forums.
These people are likely to work hard at school or in the office.
They certainly don't spend their Thursday mornings wandering around Berwick Street record stores, flipping through records and avoiding the gaze of a creepy, 30-year-old faux television presenter as he peers over the shoulders of unsuspecting middle-aged men.
