The longest-lived vertebrate in the world was found - an ice shark can live up to 400 years
The Greenland shark (Somniosus microcephalus), known as the ice shark, does not reach sexual maturity until it is 150 years old.
It could live another 250 years after that, reports a new study.
The numbers make the species the longest-lived vertebrate in the modern world.
In the animal kingdom, it is surpassed only by the Icelandic mussel, whose oldest known specimen is dated to be 507 years old.
