Due to the slow growth rate, according to monitoring, only about one centimeter per year, adult individuals have necessarily lived for a long time.
But for how long?
Julius Nielsen from the University of Copenhagen and his colleagues found out.
He determined the ages of adult polar sharks from 28 females trapped by fishermen.
The age of the fish was revealed by radiocarbon dating of the eye lenses.
The average age of the sharks studied turned out to be at least 272 years.
The two largest fish in the sample, the 493-centimetre and 502-centimetre Amazonian fins, were revealed to be around 335 and 392 years old, respectively.
Since previous studies have shown that female ice sharks do not reach sexual maturity until they are more than four metres old, the researchers calculated that they will be around 150 years old at that point.
