In June, the British surprised themselves by voting their empire out of the EU.
In the end, 52% of voters were in favour of leaving and 48% would have remained in the Union, even though polls in polling week predicted the opposite.
British economists and economic institutions were almost unanimously in favour of staying in the EU.
No respected research institute or university flagged for resignation, even though a couple of individual researchers dared to disagree with the mainstream of their profession.
The basic mantra of Western politics, the theme phrase of former US President Bill Clinton's recent election campaign, "It's the economy, stupid", was scrapped in the Brexit vote in Britain.
Economists were shocked when their voices were not heard.
They were shocked when the economy didn't seem to be the most important thing in politics.
Economic curly language
In its latest monthly survey, the Centre for Macroeconomics asks the profession for answers to the Brexit disaster.
The most typical answer is that the economists were not listened to, because this time the voters made the decision on non-economic grounds.
One explanation for economists' loss of position in the economy is that people do not understand the economy.
Many people still have the illusion that the number of jobs is independent of the number of people in work, which is almost constant.
If an immigrant gets a job, it is taken away from a real Briton.
Many also have the impression that a fall in the value of a currency would be a good thing, as it will boost the export industry.
The economists felt that voters did not believe the economic arguments because the consensus of economists was not sufficiently expressed.
In particular, they were struck by the BBC's fairness, which gave as much space to pro-Brexit economists representing only a couple of percent of the economists as to the overwhelming majority.
The anti-EU press was not interested in telling what the IFS, IFM, BoE, CEPR and LSE and other economic grandiose combinations thought about the consequences of Brexit.
Those distant combinations of letters spoke facelessly of economic growth, trade relations, sovereign debt and currency.
And if the messages of economists were both listened to and understood, they were ignored, because economists represent an elite with whom voters do not think they have common interests.
Academics in big cities, such as economists, would have stayed in the EU, but the message did not work in small towns and rural areas.
Immigration is also an economy
The overwhelming victory argument in the Brexit vote was about immigration.
An immigrant takes your job, an immigrant overcrowds your hospital, an immigrant takes advantage of you.
These arguments worked.
Each café has foreign workers.
How many more jobs would the British have if they left?
In the waiting room of every health centre you can see immigrants.
How much easier would it be for a Briton to get doctor's appointments if they didn't exist?
Every school has children of immigrants.
How much easier would it be for the children of a real Briton to get a place in school if they were got rid of?
Every municipality is home to foreigners.
How much more space would the natives have if they disappeared?
I believe that these are economic issues.
They concern jobs, housing and public services.
