Aberdeen Real Estate Fund prepared for Brexit with cash
One of the funds was Aberdeen Asset Management, whose real estate investments are made by Finnish Pertti Vanhanen.
According to him, Aberdeen prepared for Brexit in good time by drawing up plans A and B.
Plan B, i.e. the victory of the pro-EU camp, began to be prepared for in more detail a few weeks before the vote, in case the result was to leave.
The concern was that investors would start withdrawing their funds from the market.
Real estate funds do not normally have substantial liquid assets, but now they could be necessary.
We set out to increase our cash balances.
When Brexit happened on the 23rd, we had 25 per cent of the fund's investments in cash or liquid assets," Vanhanen said of Aberdeen's only open daily real estate fund affected by the news.
According to Vanhanen, the normal level would be 15-20 per cent.
The fund was valued at £3.5 billion at the time.
In total, the company's funds are worth around £20 billion.
It was the highest amount in nine open real estate funds, Vanhanen says of all open real estate funds in Britain.
He estimated that the lowest amount of cash in these funds was ten percent or even less.
In other words, real estate funds prepared for Brexit with very different strategies.
Funds closed trading
When the pro-EU camp won, Europe went haywire.
In the real estate market, however, the less than two weeks following the vote were quite calm," Vanhanen says.
Then two things happened that changed the situation.
The first was a speech by Mark Carney, Governor of the Bank of England, in which he estimated that Brexit could be a big risk for commercial property operators.
In addition, the first real estate fund, Standard Life, froze its trading.
Together, these smashed the situation and made headlines in the Financial Times and the BBC.
The situation was immediately compared to 2007 and 2008," Vanhanen says.
This made investors nervous.
Institutional investors remained calmer, but private investors became nervous.
The snowball began to roll, and fund after fund was forced to close its doors.
Aberdeen was in a good position due to the cash collected, but it too eventually had to freeze its trading for six days.
According to Vanhanen, they did not actually close trade, but changed the pricing downwards.
In practice, he said, investors were given time to consider whether it was worth withdrawing money now in a panic.
Aberdeen's message was that if you are not forced to take your money out now, it is not worth it, because there would be losses.
This calmed the situation, and most withdrew the notification.
Since then, it has been fairly steady, and now the market has been very calm for a couple of weeks," Vanhanen says.
He points out that, for example, there has been no such turmoil in the continental funds in Aberdeen.
However, there were many inquiries.
Undue attention to real estate funds
In Vanhanen's opinion, the closures of real estate fund transactions received an unreasonable amount of attention.
Open funds, which were affected by the closures, control around four per cent of UK properties.
The lockdown in Aberdeen lasted six days, and the company sold off fewer than ten of its 80 properties in London.
Some other funds are still closed.
Aviva Investors warned investors this week that it may hold its funds closed into 2017.
At the moment, uncertainty is in the air and economic growth forecasts have been downwards, but the situation does not look "wilder" for Aberdeen.
The biggest questions now concern the future development of the British economy.
Despite the uncertainty, the situation has even brought new opportunities for some real estate investors, Vanhanen points out.
The pound-dollar exchange rate is at its weakest level in 30 years, and the market is also selling off 15% compared to before the Brexit vote.
A dollar buyer can now buy the same property for up to 30 percent cheaper.
There are many willing buyers, Vanhanen says.
Brexit brought minuses to London's property market
At two o'clock in the morning the situation did not look very good.
But at four o'clock, when Pertti Vanhanen, who is responsible for real estate investments at British real estate fund Aberdeen Asset Management, woke up again to look at the results of the Brexit vote, the situation was different.
That was the expletive.
I realised that this is now going to plan B," says Vanhanen from his second home in Helsinki.
He immediately headed to work.
The City of London was already fully alive, despite the early hours of the morning.
TV screens in the office, which were normally set to silent, broadcast the news, and the usually noisy crowd fell completely silent listening as Prime Minister David Cameron stepped in front of the camera in the morning to announce his resignation.
When the market opened, the display screens flashed nothing but red.
It was the kind of morning you never thought you would live," Vanhanen says.
Not because, despite the turmoil, Aberdeen, one of Britain's largest real estate funds, completed two property deals the day after the Brexit vote, Midsummer.
The atmosphere was mixed.
However, the company had prepared well for the alternative, which is why the situation was calm in a way, Vanhanen says.
Brexit vote started a correction
The vote was followed by a storm.
The pound collapsed, the British leadership went into a change.
The markets began to anticipate drastic declines in the British and especially London property markets.
London office space was predicted to be negatively impacted by up to 20% in the coming years.
Soon, a number of British real estate funds began freezing their trading one after another.
Aberdeen did so for six days.
Now the storm has subsided, but uncertainty is still in the air.
However, it is not visible on the face of Vanhanen, who spent his last summer holidays in Helsinki this week.
He thinks it's far too early to say much about what the consequences of Brexit will be.
So much remains open: how the separation will take place and how Scotland will react to the situation, for example.
Initial data on developments in the London property market have already been received.
Real estate services company CBRE's data on price development cover about a third of the market.
According to them, prices of all properties in London fell by 3.3% between June and July.
In office buildings in the City of London, the negative figure was 6.1 per cent, Vanhanen lists.
The figures are not so terrible, but they are monthly changes.
The monthly index began to be published in 1987, and there have only been worse figures in five months," says Vanhanen.
All equally large drops occurred during the crisis years of 2007 and 2008.
It is also interesting because Brexit was compared quite quickly to the collapse of Lehman and the global economic crisis that started on the US property market.
In Vanhanen's opinion, the comparison is not quite apt, as this is now Britain's homespun crisis.
The mood is also different.
The real estate market has not seen panic selling like that at the time, but a willingness to sell to improve liquidity," Vanhanen says.
Funding is also available normally.
A correction could have been imminent anyway
In fact, a price correction is no wonder to him – it could have happened even without Brexit.
Aberdeen estimates that property prices in London and other world-leading cities have been too high for years.
We have been saying for two years now that City, and especially offices, are overpriced," says Vanhanen.
So the drop started really high.
Prices in London have climbed upwards for four reasons, Vanhanen lists.
Britain's economy has grown strongly, London's population as well.
Another big trend is that real estate is the last ownership class to become globalised, Vanhanen says.
New players have entered the market from the Middle East and Asia, and more and more institutions and even private investors are looking for real estate investments abroad.
As a well-known city, London is an easy destination.
In addition, prices have been fuelled by low interest rates, which has forced pension companies, for example, to seek income from new targets.
On top of this, loans have been readily available – although, according to Vanhanen, leverage has now been used clearly less than during the boom before the 2008 crisis.
Decentralize, decentralize
In London, the rise in prices levelled off last summer," says Vanhanen.
Aberdeen also began to lighten its holdings in London, and was a net seller last year.
Some kind of turnaround was expected, and now it came.
Where do we go from here?
It depends on how the British economy develops," Vanhanen says.
He does not dare to estimate much about the future, but says that there is unlikely to be an upward spike.
The mood suggests that there is a downward or steady pace ahead.
Vanhanen has already seen several moves up and down, as he has been in the real estate business since 1988.
And he is still an optimist who believes that the potholes can be overcome with work.
If you are well prepared for risks, you are in a better position.
He believes in global decentralization.
If you have invested in one market, you are too much of a victim.
If you have diversified, the risks are also diversified," Vanhanen says.
