Video: Heila puppy is Customs' newest dog reinforcement - puppy becomes first explosive dog
A black Labrador puppy vigorously sniffs five identical boxes lined up on the ground at Helsinki Airport.
It doesn't take long for it to sit firmly next to the middle drawer.
Customs inspector Lassi Suntio rewards his dog Heila by playing with her favourite toy.
The box next to which Heila sat revealed a jar full of gunpowder gas shells.
Gunpowder gas is the first smell we have now practiced with Heila, says Suntio, owner of Heila the dog.
Security situation and e-commerce main reasons
Heila is Customs' first dog specialising in weapons and explosives search, and it will be assigned to work at Helsinki Airport next year.
If necessary, the tasks may also take Heila and Suntio to other border crossing points and ports.
However, the airport will be Heila's main place of work, as the international security situation has changed due to serious terrorist attacks in Europe.
The attacks in Paris and Brussels prompted measures at Customs, and controls have been strengthened after the attacks," says Mikko Grönberg, Senior Officer at Customs.
Another main reason for training firearms and explosives dogs for Customs' duties is postal consignments passing through Helsinki Airport.
As a result of increased internet sales, up to 40 million postal items pass through the airport every year, including military equipment and explosives ordered from abroad.
In recent years, Customs has made around 300 discoveries related to weapons, weapon parts, ammunition and explosives and their precursors among online purchases, passenger aircraft luggage and air freight at Helsinki Airport.
Heila will work in different parts of Helsinki Airport.
It will examine checked baggage and mail.
In ports, it will be of great benefit in the future, as it can go through large container areas and mark areas that require more detailed research," says Grönberg.
Based on Heila's performance, Customs will assess whether more firearms and explosives dogs will be trained in the future.
Grönberg is optimistic about the idea.
School in Kirkkonummi
Heila's puppy training is coordinated by the Customs dog school in Kirkkonummi.
Suntio also attends training with Heila with experts from the police and the Finnish Defence Forces.
The police have strong experience in training dogs and the Finnish Defence Forces have expertise in explosives.
Together with other authorities, Customs decides which odours Heila is taught to identify.
Heila is trained further as needed, says Grönberg.
Heila's colleagues at Helsinki Airport include Customs' six sniffer dogs and Massi, a money and sniffer dog.
Labrador Retriever Heila has been selected from a litter of ten puppies.
The selection criteria for a dog selected for the airport include briskness and hunting instinct, as well as calmness, because the dog is dealing with weapons, explosives and streams of people.
Heila, who lives at Suntio's home, is a close colleague of the customs inspector, but also a family member.
You can't get anywhere at home without Heila, Suntio laughs.
Subtle orders are delivered to Heila from a one-time medication.
The cameraman of the Ilta-Sanomat newspaper loses the camera mic cover to the fast dog, but Heila immediately returns the protective cover, which looks like a soft toy, on the "off" order.
Tough competition for working dogs
Heila's initial training will be completed next year.
There are still level tests ahead, next in October, to assess whether the training is sufficient for demanding tasks.
Heila can be seen working at Helsinki Airport next year if everything goes according to plan.
Unfortunately, passengers cannot come and pet a dog wearing a work vest, Suntio reminds us.
The cost of one working dog is approximately 60,000–70,000 euros per year for Customs.
Their working life is about seven to eight years, even ten, after which they retire to the care of their owner.
Working days can be long, from eight to ten hours, but active work takes only ten minutes to a couple of hours.
Customs faces fierce competition for the ownership of working dogs.
About 20-30 Customs employees applied to become Heila's owner.
Suntio was lucky, as he has never had a working dog before, but he has years of experience with dogs and control tasks at Customs.
