The forest gift deduction is one tax change in the Ministry of Finance's budget proposal for next year.
A tax deduction is proposed for the Income Tax Act, which would be granted on the basis of gift tax on generational change of a forest holding.
In the proposal of the Ministry of Finance, the forest gift deduction has four objectives: to promote generational renewal of forest holdings, to rejuvenate the age structure of forest owners, to increase the size of forest holdings and to increase the supply of wood.
The aim of the Ministry is to promote entrepreneurial forestry.
The forest owner would make a deduction from the pure capital income from forestry.
In general, the idea of creating a tool like this to promote generational renewal of forest holdings is a good one, comments Juha Hakkarainen, Director of Forestry at the Central Union of Agricultural Producers and Forest Owners (MTK).
However, Hakkarainen finds criticism in the tax amendment proposal.
It is proposed that the deduction for forest gifts be made from the forest owner's pure capital income.
It is income from capital minus all other deductions.
According to MTK and Hakkarainen, the impact of the tax deduction would be greater if the deduction could be made directly from the income from the sale of wood.
The Ministry of Finance's proposal is based on the assumption that by deducting pure capital income from forestry, it will prevent it from causing losses on capital income from forestry that would be deductible in other taxation.
Such a person would receive a tax benefit even if he did not sell the wood.
The calculation model is unnecessarily complicated.
The average forest owner is unable to perceive it," Hakkarainen says.
In addition, according to him, the model only applies to a small percentage of forest owners.
In the proposal, the tax deduction limit tied to the yield value of forests is EUR 40,000.
In Hakkarainen's opinion, it has been drawn too high.
As such, he says, it will remove 82 per cent of Finnish forest owners from the scope of the reduction.
The model would have an impact on about 10 per cent of forest owners," he says.
The Ministry of Finance considers that the limit guarantees the goal of increasing the size of farms.
According to Hakkarainen, the reduction in forest gifts has been pushed for decades in forest policy.
This is due to the ageing of forest owners.
According to MTK, the average age of forest owners is currently over 60 years, and about half of forest owners are pensioners.
