Trampoline peace in the midst of the Olympic frenzy
Wherever you are, whatever time it is, the Olympics are on.
The events in Rio de Janeiro feel constant and inevitable, a furious message of competition and effort.
It's as if the Olympic torch itself were a flaming baton passed from archer to swimmer and gymnast to triathlete.
It's impossible to turn on the TV, read the newspaper, or listen to a conversation with someone next to you in line at a café without hearing about Simone Biles, Katie Ledecky, or the feud between Michael Phelps and Chad le Clos.
And then there's Logan Dooley.
Dooley, an Olympic first-timer and future heartthrob with his smile pits, could well be one of those well-known names presented in prime time, backed by sponsorship deals and feel-good TV commercials - if he were a swimmer, gymnast or even a fencer.
But Dooley, 28, from Lake Forest, California, is competing for Olympic gold on the trampoline.
The Olympic flame does not illuminate all sports equally.
Further from the center, partly in the shade, are those sports that are not generally accepted by everyone: air pistol shooting, archery, badminton, taekwondo.
We always have breaststroke, long live it.
But if I may make a fair number of my special favorite, I would like to draw attention to the subdued charm of the trampoline.
Although the trampoline has been an Olympic sport since 2000, when it first debuted at the Sydney Games, its presence has received so little attention in the past 16 years that many of the people I interviewed didn't realize it was an Olympic sport at all.
This may be regional ignorance.
Although the United States has sent athletes to compete in the sport, it has never won a medal in it, and its athlete did not advance to the finals until 2012.
The Chinese and Russians usually share men's, Chinese and Canadian women's medals.
This year, China's Dong Dong and Canada's Rosie McLennan will defend their London gold medals.
However, there is a certain underdog charm associated with the trampoline, partly because to the unsophisticated ear it sounds more suitable for clown school than for the Olympics.
Here I must confess that I am not an expert, I am just a flightless fan.
The sport has the potential for amusement, as can be seen from the vibrations of the endless bounces in cartoons, but it also has the gracefulness of gymnastics and diving, two sports that basically combine in it.
The word "trampoline" comes from the Spanish word el trampolín, which means springboard.
Championship seekers jump on a giant trampoline up to nearly 30 feet high and must perform spinning sequences of movements (turns, folds and flips) and eventually land on their feet.
According to the official program of the Olympic Games, they are judged by execution, difficulty and "flight time".
32 athletes from 17 countries, 16 men and 16 women, will compete in Rio.
The most common direction of the Olympics is straight ahead.
Those hoping for a medal have to go further, faster, up and over in search of gold - sometimes all the way to the finish line, sometimes back and forth around the field.
They are not only hunting for the finish line or the starting wall, but also, in televised coverage, for another mocking border: a world or Olympic record.
This purposeful pursuit is noble, admirable and even fanatical - and it can even bring the viewer to tears.
But it's also the reason why watching the races can be a bit exhausting.
The trampoline offers a moment of rest here.
The direction of the trampoline is up.
The goal is not to move forward.
The competitor soars to a new ascent, appearing weightless like an astronaut, goes up, then down, then effortlessly up again.
Of course, this is not lacking in competition and difficulty, but during the program there is no furious rush towards the end, no jumps into the distance, just a dreamlike, graceful interruption of time and gravity.
It's as close to zen as can be achieved at the Olympics.
The women's qualifying competitions and then the final will take place on Friday afternoon with the broadcast starting at 1 p.m. (ET), the men's races will also come on Saturday at 1 p.m.
NBC will broadcast the finals as part of its afternoon programming, starting at 2 p.m. both days.
Amidst the Olympic frenzy, they offer a quiet, charming moment that probably won't go unnoticed in the general chaos.
And if awareness is only achieved by offering male athletes to stare at and objectify (as U.S. male gymnasts recently suggested, according to The Wall Street Journal), Dooley is just waiting to sigh at his new fan base.
'Generation demonstrates' in Ethiopia, a longtime ally of the U.S.
Violent protests in Ethiopia
Protesters demanding political change in Ethiopia have faced violent opposition from the government.
Eyewitnesses say dozens of protesters have been shot dead in clashes with police.
Is Ethiopia crumbling?
Over the past decade, it has been one of Africa's most stable states, a firm ally of the West with a rapidly growing economy.
In recent months, however, anti-government protests have shaken the country as they spread to more and more regions.
Last week alone, thousands of people took to the streets demanding fundamental political change.
Human rights groups said the government's response was relentless.
Witnesses said police shot and killed dozens of unarmed protesters.
Videos that have circulated, recorded at the protests, believed to be late last year or early this year, show security officials beating young people with sticks while they were forced to stand with their hands against a wall.
The United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights is now calling for a thorough investigation.
"Keeping this country together was always difficult, and it will be even more so in the future," said Rashid Abdi, project manager for the Horn of Africa at the International Crisis Group.
Ethiopia is the second most populous country in Africa after Nigeria, and Western countries value its stability.
America's military and intelligence services work closely with the Ethiopians in the fight against terrorist threats in the region, particularly in Somalia, and hardly any African country receives so much Western aid.
Ethiopia's economy has grown at an impressive rate.
Its infrastructure has improved immensely, and there is even a new commuter train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
City streets are typically quiet, safe and clean.
Although Ethiopia has not been a model of democracy. Human rights organisations have constantly spoken of government repression, opposition in the country has been limited, and dissent has been effectively silenced.
Many have been deported, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the desert.
But this may be changing.
"If you suppress people and they have no choice but to demonstrate, this is what will happen," Seyoum Teshome, a university lecturer from central Ethiopia, said.
All young people are demonstrating.
One generation is demonstrating.
The complaints are manifold and cover everything from land use to the stranglehold of power of the ruling coalition.
After last year's much-criticised elections, the ruling party and its allies won the last seat held by the opposition and now holds all the seats in parliament.
At the same time, tensions on the border with Eritrea are rising. The battle along this tense and disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Analysts fear that separatist groups such as the Oromo Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, which have been more or less defeated in recent years, may try to exploit the turmoil and rearm themselves.
Numerous factors explain why, after years of turmoil beneath the surface, bitter feelings are now exploding.
The first seems seemingly harmless: smartphones.
Only in the last few years have a large number of Ethiopians been able to communicate through social media, as cheaper smartphones have become more common and internet service has improved.
Even if the government closes access to Facebook and Twitter, as it often does, especially during protests, many people can still communicate through online proxies that hide their location.
Many young Ethiopians said that this is how they gathered for the demonstrations.
Secondly, Ethiopia's two largest ethnic groups, the Oromo and Amhara, get along better.
The Oromo and Amharic are not natural allies.
For a very long time, the Amharas, who come from the predominantly Christian highlands of Ethiopia, prospered in politics and business, taking advantage of the Oromas, many of whom are Muslims and who live in the lowlands.
But that, too, is changing.
"We are heading towards organizing under one umbrella," Oromo leader Mulatu Gemechu said.
The largest demonstrations have been in the Amhara and Oromo regions.
Many Amharas and Oromo think that Ethiopia is unfairly ruled by Tigre people. The nation covers about six percent of the population and controls the armed forces, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third reason for the unrest is the loss of Meles Zenawi.
Meles, a former rebel leader, was prime minister of Ethiopia for 17 years until he died of a secret illness in 2012.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who saw around corners.
Analysts say he was particularly qualified at observing early signs of discontent and using secret envoys to neutralize opponents.
"The current regime doesn't have that kind of basic instinct," conflict analyst Abdi said.
Ethiopia's new prime minister, Hailemariam Desalegn, was picked relatively unknown to fill Meles' boots.
Unlike Meles, who was native to the Tigre region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam is from the south.
Analysts say he is not trusted by Tigrayan-controlled security services.
Many fear that this may lead to increased bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia was in such turmoil was in 2005, when thousands protested about elections which, according to analysts, looked like the government first shook and then plundered them.
In the ensuing crackdown, many demonstrators were killed, albeit fewer than in recent months, and that period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts have praised Ethiopia's leaders for visionary infrastructure planning, such as a new commuter train, and significant advances in the fight against poverty.
But clearly this has not stopped the growing contempt for the Ethiopian Government within the country.
And now it is beginning to take on a dangerous, ethnic form.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked Tigrayan-owned businesses, and anti-Tigre hatred is becoming increasingly common on social media.
Analysts say the protests put the United States and other Western allies in a clumsy position.
The American government has used Ethiopia as a base for drone flights to neighboring Somalia, even though it recently said it had closed this base.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, it also does not want its ally in an already unstable region to collapse.
"This," Abdi said, "is a real balancing act."
