NASA Climate Model: Venus Was Once Habitable
According to estimates of NASA's new climate model, Venus was likely once habitable.
Scientists at NASA's Goddard Institute for Space Studies developed a model to study Venus' past using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to find out whether Venus, with its hot, waterless surfaces and carbon dioxide-filled atmosphere, could ever have had Earth-like conditions.
Scientists have previously suggested that the slow speed of rotation of Venus is explained by its thick atmosphere.
But the latest simulation suggests that Venus could have had a thin, Earth-like atmosphere, and could still have rotated slowly.
The model also looked at the topography of early Venus.
There were probably drier areas of the planet than Earth, but there was once enough water and geographical variation to enable life and protect against rapid evaporation of water.
Early Venus also had the advantage of having a 30 percent fainter sun.
"In a simulation of the GISS model, Venus' slow rotation reveals its daytime side to the Sun for nearly two months at a time," GISS researcher Anthony Del Genio explained in a news release.
This warms the surface and produces rain, which creates a thick layer of clouds that acts as an umbrella, protecting the surface from much of the sun's heat.
As a result, average global temperatures are actually a few degrees cooler than Earth's current levels.
The model produced a story about Venus' evolution similar to what planetary scientists had previously assumed.
Although Venus was probably once habitable, it was exposed to excessive heat and ultraviolet light over several billion years.
Its oceans evaporated and its water vapors burned under ultraviolet light.
When its hydrogen escaped, all that was left was a thick carbon dioxide atmosphere with deadly greenhouse gas phenomena - Venus as we know it today.
The researchers shared the results of their new Venus climate model in Geophysical Research Letters.
