In order to achieve this, the vision of the coach and vice president of hockey affairs must be fully aligned with that of the organization.
He must also have the opportunity to influence decisions that affect the team's performance.
These conditions are not currently met.
Sakic, who hired Roy on May 23, 2013, thanked Roy for his contribution to the team.
"Patrick told me today about his decision," Sakic said.
We appreciate everything he has done for the organization and wish him the best of luck in the future.
Roy was named the Jack Adams Award for the league's best coach in his first season with the Avalanche in 2013-14.
He led the team to 112 points and a Central Division victory, but Minnesota knocked out Colorado in the first round of the playoffs and the team hasn't qualified for the past two years.
The Avalanche's games in the 2015-16 season ended with 39 wins, 39 losses and 4 draws, and the team lost by five points to the Wild, losing the Western Conference wild card playoff spot.
Hall of Fame inductee Roy won four Stanley Cups — two with both the Montreal Canadiens and Avalanche.
North Sea oil workers continue negotiations and postpone strike
North Sea oil workers' industrial action over pay will be postponed as all sides in the dispute sit down for a new round of talks, leading negotiators said.
Strikes against oilfield services company Wood Group have been held sporadically on North Sea drilling platforms run by Royal Dutch Shell.
"Wood Group and the Unite and RMT unions can confirm that we have agreed to resume the process of resolving the current dispute," the joint statement read.
We will hold a number of full-day meetings over the next few weeks, starting early next week, in order to take a fresh look at the problems.
Trade unions say their recent industrial action, which they say is the first in more than 25 years, was a protest against possible pay cuts of up to 30%.
This year, Wood Group cut North Sea contractor fees by around 9% due to negative market pressure.
The company's fee deduction follows a 10 per cent reduction for contractors in its countries for 2014.
The company said further cuts would give the company the leeway it needs to survive the market downturn.
Shell, meanwhile, has cut thousands of people from its payroll and announced plans to leave oil and gas operations in as many as 10 countries as the company streamlines operations following its giant merger with British energy company BG Group.
Energy companies are under pressure due to lower crude oil prices, and this economic situation is exacerbated by Britain's decision to leave the European Union in June.
Scottish MP Dave Anderson met with union leaders earlier this week to discuss one of the biggest North Sea labour disputes in a generation.
He said that the North Sea is essential to the region's economy.
"We need an economy that works for many, not just a few, both in the North Sea and across the country," he said in a statement.
The North Sea is expected to receive less than $1.4 billion of investment in new projects in 2016, compared to an average of about $7 billion over the past five years.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of stars in the Pleiades Cluster
The latest mission by the Kepler Space Telescope has helped astronomers compile the most complete inventory of the rotational velocities of stars in the Pleiades Cluster.
The new data will help astronomers understand why stars in a cluster rotate at varying speeds, as well as how orbital periods relate to planet formation.
"We hope that by comparing our results with other star clusters, we will now learn more about the relationship between the mass of a star, its age and even the history of its solar system," Luisa Rebull, a researcher at Caltech's Center for Infrared Processing and Analysis in Pasadena, said in a press release
The Pleiades Cluster is located 445 light-years from Earth.
Many of the stars in the cluster were born about 125 million years ago and are now reaching adulthood.
They are now spinning at their peak level.
At their peak rotational speeds, these maturing stars spew large amounts of stellar wind.
When these winds travel through the magnetic fields of stars, they brake the stars.
As the star ages, its rotational speed begins to slow down.
Kepler measures the rotational speed of each star by tracking the appearance of recognizable star spots, such as sunspots.
The latest list of stellar rotational velocities suggests that more massive stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares the stars to dancers, with the bigger ones doing pirouettes more slowly than the smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that slow spinners tend to be more massive, while the fastest spinners tend to be very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades Cluster is so close, it is an ideal cosmic laboratory for assessing stellar properties at rotational speeds.
"The Pleiades cluster provides anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation that encompass both directions, younger and older," Rebull said.
We still have a lot to learn about how, when and why stars slow down their rotation speed and, so to speak, hang up their 'dance shoes' on a nail.
Rebull and his colleagues described their latest analysis of the rotational velocities of the Pleiades in three papers to be published soon in the Astronomical Journal.
